From a customer's email:
{quote}Also, coming from a trac/redmine background, I think it would behoove Atlassian to figure out 'project' based navigation instead of 'application' based navigation. That is, I would like to see a common header for the project I am working on, and then sub-tabs for the different apps within that project ... not the other way around.{quote}

A 'projects' tab in the header that then gives you an overall view of projects would probably also satisfy.

The Subversion permission manager appears to be unable to revoke a permission granted at the root path. For instance, given the default root permissions:

!svnperms_root.png!

and a project FOO:

!svnperms_proj.png!

Clicking 'remove' on the *users* entry just causes the screen to refresh.

However, actually the change has taken effect!  The FOO project's section in the {{authz}} file has changed from:

{noformat}
 [/FOO]
 @developers = rw
 @administrators = rw
 @users = r
 @_no-one-at-all = r
 _bamboo-svn-user = r
{noformat}

to:

{noformat}
 [/FOO]
 @users = 
 @developers = rw
 @administrators = rw
 @_no-one-at-all = r
 _bamboo-svn-user = r
{noformat}

The 5 minute cache on the {{authz}} file can further mislead an administrator that the change hasn't taken effect, when it has.

Also, it's now not possible to grant read access to the users group, because the UI thinks the group already has access.

Say I configure a particular path in terms of a group, which I later delete.  The Subversion permission manager will still show the group with its associated permission, reflecting what is in the authz file.  Trying to perform any operation will result in an error.

For instance, here the 'developers' group has been removed, but is still referenced in {{authz}} with:

{noformat}
[/]
@developers = rw
@administrators = rw
@users = r
@_no-one-at-all = r
_bamboo-svn-user = r
{noformat}

The SVN permission manager breaks with:

!svnperm_nogroup.png!

Certain Studio hosts have been deployed with mixed-case host names (https://MySite.jira.com vs. https://mysite.jira.com).   This mixed-case is faithfully reproduced in the Subversion checkout instructions shown in Fisheye:

{noformat}
This project is using Subversion. You may check out the source code by running: 
svn checkout https://MySite.jira.com/svn/FOO/trunk FOO --username jturner
{noformat}

This was not an issue until Studio 1.8.3, when we upgraded Subversion from 1.5 to 1.6.  Now attempting to checkout a mixed-case URL breaks with:

{noformat}
svn: Path 'https://MySite.jira.com/svn/FOO/trunk' is not canonicalized; there is a problem with the client.
{noformat}

Worse still, operations on existing checkouts give the same error.

{code}
com.thoughtworks.xstream.converters.ConversionException: Cannot construct com.atlassian.applinks.core.DefaultApplicationLink as it does not have a no-args constructor
{code}
